750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*roIeve1WkHgIno11knpnPA.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*roIeve1WkHgIno11knpnPA.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*roIeve1WkHgIno11knpnPA.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*roIeve1WkHgIno11knpnPA.png 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/700/1*roIeve1WkHgIno11knpnPA.png"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">The structural formula of benzene (C₆H₆) proposed by the 19th-century German chemist August Kekulé and a modern depiction of the benzene ring. According to a legend, Kekulé’s insight came after a dream in which he saw a snake biting its own tail.</p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">In the first half of the 20th century, with the rapid growth of newly discovered compounds and their commercial use, the problem of organising, searching, and comparing molecules became of crucial importance: for example, when a pharmaceutical company sought to patent a new drug, the Patent Office had to verify whether a similar compound had been previously deposited.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">To address this challenge, several systems for indexing molecules were introduced in the 1940s, forming foundations for a new discipline that would later be called <em>chemoinformatics</em>. One such system, named the ‘GKD chemical cipher’ after the authors Gordon, Kendall, and Davison [4], was developed at the English tire firm Dunlop to be used with early punchcard-based computers [5]. In essence, the GKD cipher was an algorithm for parsing a molecular structure into a string that could be more easily looked up by a human or a computer.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
