750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*Q9SiU32xhe6MX4iwC_jshg.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*Q9SiU32xhe6MX4iwC_jshg.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*Q9SiU32xhe6MX4iwC_jshg.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*Q9SiU32xhe6MX4iwC_jshg.png 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/700/1*Q9SiU32xhe6MX4iwC_jshg.png"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">Example of a chemical compound and its ciphers according to different systems. Image from [13].</p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><span>H</span>owever, the GKD cipher and other related methods [6] were far from satisfactory. In chemical compounds, similar structures often result in similar properties. Chemists are trained to develop intuition to spot such analogies, and look for them when comparing compounds. For example, the association of the benzene ring with odouriferous properties was the reason for the naming of the chemical class of “aromatic compounds” in the 19th century.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">On the other hand, when a molecule is represented as a string (such as in the GKD cipher), the constituents of a single chemical structure may be mapped into different positions of the cipher. As a result, two molecules containing a similar substructure (and thus possibly similar properties) might be encoded in very different ways.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*lXTDimQZfmbwlCHyRYm1UA.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*lXTDimQZfmbwlCHyRYm1UA.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*lXTDimQZfmbwlCHyRYm1UA.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*lXTDimQZfmbwlCHyRYm1UA.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*lXTDimQZfmbwlCHyRYm1UA.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*lXTDimQZfmbwlCHyRYm1UA.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*lXTDimQZfmbwlCHyRYm1UA.png 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*lXTDimQZfmbwlCHyRYm1UA.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*lXTDimQZfmbwlCHyRYm1UA.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*lXTDimQZfmbwlCHyRYm1UA.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*lXTDimQZfmbwlCHyRYm1UA.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*lXTDimQZfmbwlCHyRYm1UA.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*lXTDimQZfmbwlCHyRYm1UA.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*lXTDimQZfmbwlCHyRYm1UA.png 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/700/1*lXTDimQZfmbwlCHyRYm1UA.png"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">A figure from George Vlăduţ’s 1959 paper [13] showing a chemical molecule and its fragment along with the corresponding GKD-ciphers. Note that this coding system breaks the spatial locality of connected atoms in the molecule, such that the fragment cipher cannot be found by simple substring matching in that of the full molecule. This drawback of early chemical representation methods was one of the motivations for the search of structural representations of molecules as graphs.</p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><span>T</span>his realisation has encouraged the development of “topological ciphers,” trying to capture the structure of the molecule. First works of this kind were done in the Dow Chemicals company [7] and the US Patent Office [8] — both heavy users of chemical databases. One of the most famous such descriptors, known as the ‘Morgan fingerprint’ [9], was developed by Harry Morgan at the Chemical Abstracts Service [10] and used until today.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">Chemistry Meets Graph Theory</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">A figure that has played a key role in developing early “structural” approaches for searching chemical databases is the Romanian-born Soviet researcher George Vlăduţ [11]. A chemist by training (he defended a PhD in organic chemistry at the Moscow Mendeleev Institute in 1952), he experienced a traumatic encounter with the gargantuan Beilstein handbook in his freshman years [12]. This steered his research interests towards chemoinformatics [13], a field in which he worked for the rest of his life.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Vlăduţ is credited as one of the pioneers of using graph theory for modeling the structures and reactions of chemical compounds. In a sense, this should not come as a surprise: graph theory has been historically tied to chemistry, and even the term ‘graph’ (referring to a set of nodes and edges, rather than a plot of a function) was introduced by the mathematician <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Joseph_Sylvester" target="_self">James Sylvester</a> in 1878 as a mathematical abstraction of chemical molecules [14].</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*I14igKnjCDatp9D-4T0ZjQ.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*I14igKnjCDatp9D-4T0ZjQ.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*I14igKnjCDatp9D-4T0ZjQ.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*I14igKnjCDatp9D-4T0ZjQ.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*I14igKnjCDatp9D-4T0ZjQ.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*I14igKnjCDatp9D-4T0ZjQ.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*I14igKnjCDatp9D-4T0ZjQ.png 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*I14igKnjCDatp9D-4T0ZjQ.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*I14igKnjCDatp9D-4T0ZjQ.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*I14igKnjCDatp9D-4T0ZjQ.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*I14igKnjCDatp9D-4T0ZjQ.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*I14igKnjCDatp9D-4T0ZjQ.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*I14igKnjCDatp9D-4T0ZjQ.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*I14igKnjCDatp9D-4T0ZjQ.png 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/700/1*I14igKnjCDatp9D-4T0ZjQ.png"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">The term “graph” (in the sense used in graph theory) was first introduced as a model of molecules by James Sylvester in an 1878 <em>Nature </em>note [14].</p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">In particular, Vlăduţ advocated the formulation of molecular structure comparison as the graph isomorphism problem; his most famous work was on classifying chemical reactions as the partial isomorphism (maximum common subgraph) of the reactant and product molecules [15].</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Vlăduţ’s work inspired [16] a pair of young researchers, Boris Weisfeiler (an algebraic geometer) and Andrey Lehman [17] (self-described as a “programmer” [18]). In a classical joint paper [19], the duo introduced an iterative algorithm for testing whether a pair of graphs are isomorphic (i.e., the graphs have the same structure up to reordering of nodes), which became known as the <a href="https://medium.com/expressive-power-of-graph-neural-networks-and-the-weisefeiler-lehman-test-b883db3c7c49?sk=5c2a28ccd38db3a7b6f80f161e825a5a" target="_self">Weisfeiler-Lehman (WL) test</a> [20]. Though the two had known each other from school years, their ways parted shortly after their publication and each became accomplied in his respective field [21].</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Weisfeiler and Lehman’s initial conjecture that their algorithm solved the graph isomorphism problem (and does it in polynomial time) was incorrect: while Lehman demonstrated it computationally for graphs with at most nine nodes [22], a larger counterexample was found a year later [23] (and in fact, a strongly regular graph failing the WL test called the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shrikhande_graph" target="_self">Shrinkhande graph</a><em> </em>had been known even earlier [24]).</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*jQ0Q7vwgfNrCTrZVb1-JDQ.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*jQ0Q7vwgfNrCTrZVb1-JDQ.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*jQ0Q7vwgfNrCTrZVb1-JDQ.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*jQ0Q7vwgfNrCTrZVb1-JDQ.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*jQ0Q7vwgfNrCTrZVb1-JDQ.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*jQ0Q7vwgfNrCTrZVb1-JDQ.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*jQ0Q7vwgfNrCTrZVb1-JDQ.png 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*jQ0Q7vwgfNrCTrZVb1-JDQ.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*jQ0Q7vwgfNrCTrZVb1-JDQ.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*jQ0Q7vwgfNrCTrZVb1-JDQ.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*jQ0Q7vwgfNrCTrZVb1-JDQ.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*jQ0Q7vwgfNrCTrZVb1-JDQ.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*jQ0Q7vwgfNrCTrZVb1-JDQ.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*jQ0Q7vwgfNrCTrZVb1-JDQ.png 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/700/1*jQ0Q7vwgfNrCTrZVb1-JDQ.png"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">The graph isomorphism test introduced by Andrei Lehman and Boris Weisfeiler in 1968.</p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The paper of Weisfeiler and Lehman has become foundational in understanding graph isomorphism. To put their work of in historical perspective, one should remember that in the 1960s, complexity theory was still embryonic and algorithmic graph theory was only taking its first baby steps. As Lehman recollected in the late 1990s,</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content7 cid-ttbhFZC4Ql" id="content7-8" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
        <div class="container"><div class="row justify-content-center"><div class="col-12 col-md-9"><blockquote><p class="ff4">“in the 60s, one could in matter of days re-discover all the facts, ideas, and techniques in graph isomorphism theory. I doubt, that the word ’theory’ is applicable; everything was at such a basic level.” — Andrey Lehman, 1999</p></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Their result spurred numerous follow-up works, including high-dimensional graph isomorphism tests [25]. In the context of graph neural networks, Weisfeiler and Lehman have recently become household names with the proof of the equivalence of their graph isomorphism test to message passing [26–27].</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">Early Graph Neural Networks</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><span>T</span>hough chemists have been using GNN-like algorithms for decades, it is likely that their works on molecular representation remained practically unknown in the machine learning community [28]. We find it hard to pinpoint precisely when the concept of graph neural networks has begun to emerge: partly due to the fact that most of the early work did not place graphs as a first-class citizen, partly since graph neural networks became practical only in the late 2010s, and partly because this field emerged from the confluence of several adjacent research areas.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Early forms of graph neural networks can be traced back at least to the 1990s, with examples including “Labeling RAAM” by Alessandro Sperduti [29], the “backpropagation through structure” by Christoph Goller and Andreas Küchler [30], and adaptive processing of data structures [31–32]. While these works were primarily concerned with operating over “structures” (often trees or directed acyclic graphs), many of the invariances preserved in their architectures are reminiscent of the GNNs more commonly in use today.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*sDypozSK-UEO6rlbCGSnIQ.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*sDypozSK-UEO6rlbCGSnIQ.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*sDypozSK-UEO6rlbCGSnIQ.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*sDypozSK-UEO6rlbCGSnIQ.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*sDypozSK-UEO6rlbCGSnIQ.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*sDypozSK-UEO6rlbCGSnIQ.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*sDypozSK-UEO6rlbCGSnIQ.png 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*sDypozSK-UEO6rlbCGSnIQ.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*sDypozSK-UEO6rlbCGSnIQ.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*sDypozSK-UEO6rlbCGSnIQ.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*sDypozSK-UEO6rlbCGSnIQ.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*sDypozSK-UEO6rlbCGSnIQ.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*sDypozSK-UEO6rlbCGSnIQ.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*sDypozSK-UEO6rlbCGSnIQ.png 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/700/1*sDypozSK-UEO6rlbCGSnIQ.png"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">Towards graph neural networks: early works from the 1990s focused on learning on generic structures such as trees or directed acyclic graphs. The term “graph neural network” was introduced in the classical papers of Marco Gori and Franco Scarselli.</p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><span>T</span>he first proper treatment of the processing of generic graph structures (and the coining of the term ‘graph neural network’) happened after the turn of the 21st century. A University of Siena team led by Marco Gori [33] and Franco Scarselli [34] proposed the first “GNN.” They relied on recurrent mechanisms, required the neural network parameters to specify contraction mappings, and thus computing node representations by searching for a fixed point — this in itself necessitated a special form of backpropagation and did not depend on node features at all. All of the above issues were rectified by the Gated GNN (GGNN) model of Yujia Li [35], which brought many benefits of modern RNNs, such as gating mechanisms [36] and backpropagation through time.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The neural network for graphs (NN4G) proposed by Alessio Micheli around the same time [37] used a feedforward rather than recurrent architecture, in fact resembling more the modern GNNs.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*CPRZDw4HWOvO1nPuDZuUEQ.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*CPRZDw4HWOvO1nPuDZuUEQ.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*CPRZDw4HWOvO1nPuDZuUEQ.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*CPRZDw4HWOvO1nPuDZuUEQ.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*CPRZDw4HWOvO1nPuDZuUEQ.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*CPRZDw4HWOvO1nPuDZuUEQ.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*CPRZDw4HWOvO1nPuDZuUEQ.png 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*CPRZDw4HWOvO1nPuDZuUEQ.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*CPRZDw4HWOvO1nPuDZuUEQ.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*CPRZDw4HWOvO1nPuDZuUEQ.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*CPRZDw4HWOvO1nPuDZuUEQ.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*CPRZDw4HWOvO1nPuDZuUEQ.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*CPRZDw4HWOvO1nPuDZuUEQ.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*CPRZDw4HWOvO1nPuDZuUEQ.png 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/700/1*CPRZDw4HWOvO1nPuDZuUEQ.png"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">Author with GNN pioneers Marco Gori and Alessandro Sperduti at WCCI 2022.</p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><span>A</span>nother important class of graph neural networks, often referred to as “spectral,” has emerged from the work of Joan Bruna and coauthors [38] using the notion of the Graph Fourier transform. The roots of this construction are in the signal processing and computational harmonic analysis communities, where dealing with non-Euclidean signals has become prominent in the late 2000s and early 2010s [39].</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Influential papers from the groups of Pierre Vandergheynst [40] and José Moura [41] popularised the notion of “Graph Signal Processing” (GSP) and the generalisation of Fourier transforms based on the eigenvectors of graph adjacency and Laplacian matrices. The graph convolutional neural networks relying on spectral filters by Michaël Defferrard [42] and Thomas Kipf and Max Welling [43] are among the most cited in the field.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">Back to the Origins</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><span>In</span> a somewhat ironic twist of fate, modern GNNs were triumphantly re-introduced to chemistry, a field they originated from, by David Duvenaud [44] as a replacement for handcrafted Morgan’s molecular fingerprints, and by Justin Gilmer [45] in the form of message-passing neural networks equivalent to the Weisfeiler-Lehman test [26–27]. After fifty years, the circle finally closed.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*cTX2HEKUIQxen7O72KGE8Q.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*cTX2HEKUIQxen7O72KGE8Q.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*cTX2HEKUIQxen7O72KGE8Q.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*cTX2HEKUIQxen7O72KGE8Q.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*cTX2HEKUIQxen7O72KGE8Q.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*cTX2HEKUIQxen7O72KGE8Q.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*cTX2HEKUIQxen7O72KGE8Q.png 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*cTX2HEKUIQxen7O72KGE8Q.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*cTX2HEKUIQxen7O72KGE8Q.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*cTX2HEKUIQxen7O72KGE8Q.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*cTX2HEKUIQxen7O72KGE8Q.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*cTX2HEKUIQxen7O72KGE8Q.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*cTX2HEKUIQxen7O72KGE8Q.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*cTX2HEKUIQxen7O72KGE8Q.png 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/700/1*cTX2HEKUIQxen7O72KGE8Q.png"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">Modern versions of graph neural networks triumphantly returned to chemistry with the works of David Duvenaud and Justin Gilmer.</p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Graph neural networks are now a standard tool in chemistry and <a href="https://medium.com/geometric-ml-becomes-real-in-fundamental-sciences-3b0d109883b5?sk=71edf33c88320cca6165fe6cde239f8c" target="_self">have already seen uses</a> in drug discovery and design pipelines. A notable accolade was claimed with the GNN-based discovery of novel antibiotic compounds [46] in 2020. DeepMind’s AlphaFold 2 [47] used equivariant attention (a form of GNN that accounts for the continuous symmetries of the atomic coordinates) in order to address the “Holy Grail” of structural biology — the problem of protein folding.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">In 1999, Andrey Lehman <a href="https://www.iti.zcu.cz/wl2018/pdf/leman.pdf" target="_self">wrote to a mathematician colleague</a> that he had the “pleasure to learn that ‘Weisfeiler-Leman’ was known and still caused interest.” He did not live to see the rise of GNNs based on his work of fifty years earlier. Nor did George Vlăduţ see the realisation of his ideas, many of which remained on paper during his lifetime. We are sure they would be proud of having stood at the origins of this new exciting field.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-10">
            <br>
                <hr class="hr5">
            <br>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">[1] Originally <em>Pharmaceutisches Central-Blatt</em>, it was the oldest German chemical abstracts journal published between 1830 and 1969.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">[2] Named after <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leopold_Gmelin" target="_self">Leopold Gmelin</a> who published the first version in 1817, the <em>Gmelins Handbuch</em> last print edition appeared in the 1990s. The database currently contains 1.5 million compounds and 1.3 million different reactions discovered between 1772 and 1995.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">[3] In 1906, the American Chemical Society authorised the publication of Chemical Abstracts, charging it with the mission of abstracting the world’s literature of chemistry and assigning an initial budget of fifteen thousand dollars. The first publication appeared in 1907 under the stewardship of William Noyes. Over a century since its establishment, the CAS contains nearly 200 million organic and inorganic substances disclosed in publications since the early 1800s.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">[4] M. Gordon, C. E. Kendall, and W. H. T. Davison, <em>Chemical Ciphering: a Universal Code as an Aid to Chemical Systematics </em>(1948), The Royal Institute of Chemistry.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">[5] A special purpose computer (“Electronic Structural Correlator”), to be used in conjunction with a punch card sorter, was proposed by the Gordon-Kendall-Davison group in connection with their system of chemical ciphering, but never built.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">[6] There were several contemporaneous systems that competed with each other, see W. J. Wisswesser, <a href="https://apps.dtic.mil/sti/pdfs/AD0685902.pdf" target="_self">107 Years of line-formula notations</a> (1968), J. Chemical Documentation 8(3):146–150.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
